   "source": [
    "# TRIQS/ModEST\n",
    "\n",
    "By this point in the tutorial, you have developed a working understanding of Dynamical Mean-Field Theory (DMFT), a powerful approach for treating strong local electronic correlations in lattice systems. You’ve seen how DMFT captures the dynamical nature of electron-electron interactions, going beyond static mean-field methods and providing a more accurate description of correlated materials.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, DMFT alone requires a model Hamiltonian, such as the Hubbard model, which simplifies the full complexity of a real material to a few essential parameters. To study real materials quantitatively, without relying on adjustable model parameters, we need to connect DMFT with a first-principles method that can supply the electronic structure and interaction parameters from the underlying atomic composition. The TRIQS/**M**odular **E**lectronic **S**tructure **T**oolkit (TRIQS/ModEST) provides the tools make this connection.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, we first review the key concepts of DFT+DMFT. Then, we present the two classes found in ModEST that are used to store and represent the two most important concepts: the one-body elements (obe) and the embedding.\n",
    "Finally, we introduce the subject of a sequence of tutorials in which you will learn how to use TRIQS/ModEST to build DMFT-type calculations in the context of electronic structure including density-functional theory (DFT) applied a real material: La$_2$CuO$_4$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1bb9d21d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## DFT + DMFT\n",
    "\n",
    "Quantum embedding methods like DFT+DMFT provide a powerful framework to describe strongly correlated materials by combining the strengths of density-functional theory (DFT) with a many-body technique such as DMFT. While DFT provides an efficient, parameter-free framework for calculating the ground-state properties of materials based on their chemical composition, it only works well for weakly correlated systems and often fails in the presence of strong local interactions. For example, those found in transition metal oxides, heavy fermion compounds, or actinides. DFT tends to delocalize electrons that, in reality, exhibit localized and strongly correlated behavior. One the other hand, DMFT is excellent at capturing strong local correlations, however it can only handle small systems due to the computational cost of solving the impurity problems.\n",
    "\n",
    "The interface between the two is made possible through the central concept of **embedding**, which is to\n",
    "1. Start from a complete description of a system.\n",
    "2. Identify the subset of degrees of freedom which are required by the higher-level many-body method.\n",
    "3. Map to a set of effective systems called impurity problems and solve.\n",
    "4. Embedded the many-body solution back onto the full lattice.\n",
    "\n",
    "In step one, DFT is used to obtain a complete description of the system. The key quantity needed from DFT is the electronic one-body Kohn-Sham Hamiltonian that we denote by $\\epsilon(\\textbf{k})$. This Hamiltonian encapsulates the material-specific information about the crystal structure, atomic species, and chemical bonding. It serves as a backbone for the full many-body problem. It is typically expressed in the Bloch band basis. This basis diagonalizes the Kohn-Sham Hamiltonian and takes advantage of the periodicity of the crystal to work in momentum space.\n",
    "\n",
    "In step two, the degrees of freedom for which we use DMFT are typically localized in space, therefore one crucial step is to construct a basis of localized orbitals and to construct the operators that goes from one basis to the other. Since this operation is often non-unitary, we call those operators the **projectors**.\n",
    "\n",
    "In step three, this is where the embedding is selected, defining the mapping between the full system and the set of impurity problems. In this step, we also solve the impurity problems using the many-method of choice, in this case DMFT.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally in step four, the solutions to our impurity problems are rotated back to the original Bloch band basis in order to be embedded back into the full lattice.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0048250b",
