   "source": [
    "## Abstraction of ModEST\n",
    "\n",
    "### One-body elements\n",
    "\n",
    "The key quantity needed from DFT is the electronic one-body Kohn-Sham Hamiltonian that we denote by $\\epsilon(\\textbf{k})$. This Hamiltonian encapsulates the material-specific information about the crystal structure, atomic species, and chemical bonding. It serves as a backbone for the full many-body problem.\n",
    "\n",
    "**One-body elements** (obe for short) contains all of the one-body information that surrounds the DMFT calculation. In particular, the DFT data, the projectors to the orbital basis and the choice of orbital to treat with DMFT. More precisely, the obe object contains four components:\n",
    "\n",
    "- `band_dispersion`: contains the band dispersion $\\epsilon^\\sigma_\\nu (\\textbf{k})$ corresponding to the energy at momentum $\\textbf{k}$, band index $\\nu$, and spin $\\sigma$.\n",
    "- `local_space`: defines the set of local orbitals composing the correlated subspace $\\mathcal{C}$ to be solved within DMFT.\n",
    "- `downfolding_projector`: contains the projectors $P^\\sigma_{m\\nu}(\\textbf{k})$ which downfold from Bloch space  $\\mathcal{B}$ (indexed by $\\nu$) to the correlated space $\\mathcal{C}$ (index by $m$).\n",
    "- (optional) `ibz_symmetry_ops`: contains the operations to symmetrize observables over the full Brillouin zone, when working in the irreducible Brillouin zone.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Embedding\n",
    "\n",
    "The embedding class describes the mapping between the impurity problems and the local correlated space $\\mathcal{C}$. The choice of embedding determines the type of many-body physics that will be captured and reembedded to the lattice, and it can easily become a bottleneck if one is not careful enough or too ambitious with the size of their many-body problems.\n",
    "\n",
    "In ModEST, we provide functions that allows to generate first a default embedding parametrization, given the `local_space` object of an obe, and then to manipulate this parametrization in order to personalize and adapt it to different problems. To understand these functions, we now detail how we characterize the mapping from the local space $\\mathcal{C}$ to the set of impurity problems.\n",
    "- Originally, the elements of the correlated local orbital set $\\mathcal{C}$ are each associated to a spin-line index $\\sigma$ and to the atom $a$, at position $R_a$ and in the orbital $m_a$. We write $\\mathcal{C} = \\{ \\chi^{R_a\\sigma}_{m_a} \\}$.\n",
    "- This set $\\mathcal{C}$ is divided into a number $N_\\alpha$ of subembeddings, each of them identified by an index $\\alpha$. The orbitals in the subembedding $\\alpha$ have new orbital indices $m_\\alpha$. Therefore, this defines a mapping from the atomic orbitals to the subembedding space: $(a, m_a) \\rightarrow (\\alpha, m_\\alpha)$. One possible operation is to **split** an atom in two different subembeddings using the `drop` function, for example splitting the $t_{2g}$ and $e_g$ orbitals of a $d$-shell. Another possible operation is to merge atoms to form a **cluster** using the `?` function, for example to perform a CDMFT calculation.\n",
    "- Each embedding $\\alpha$ is associated to an impurity problem with index $n_{\\text{imp}}$. This defines a mapping from the subembeddings to the impurity problems: $(\\alpha) \\rightarrow (n_{\\text{imp}})$. One possible case is that two different atoms are **equivalent** and map to the same impurity problem.\n",
    "- In each impurity problem, the impurity can have a structure and be block diagonal in its orbitals. Each of these block is labeled by $\\gamma$. Having a block diagonal structure makes solving the impurity model much easier.\n",
    "- The spin-like index in the subembedding space can be mapped non-trivially to the spin-like index of the associate impurity. For example, consider an antiferromagnet (AFM) with two sublattice: site A polarized up and site B polarized down. The AFM mapping allows for the subembeddings of these two sites to map to the same impurity problems, but with the spins of the site B subembedding inverted in relation to those of the site A subembedding.\n",
    "\n",
    "After solving all the impurity problems, the embedded self-energy in the $\\mathcal{C}$ can be obtained as \n",
    "$$[\\Sigma_{\\mathrm{embed}}]^{\\sigma}_{(\\alpha, m_{\\alpha}), (\\alpha, m_{\\alpha}')} = [\\Sigma_{\\mathrm{imp}}]^{n_{\\mathrm{imp}(\\alpha)},\\tau(\\sigma)}_{(\\gamma(\\alpha), m_{\\alpha}),(\\gamma(\\alpha), m_{\\alpha}')}.$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that all the rotations (e.g. local to global coordinate systems) have been absorbed in the projector $P$ during the basis preparation, which makes the embedding itself very simple. We first prepare the proper basis for the embedding, and then perform the embedding."
   ]
  },
