    "# Tutorials\n",
    "\n",
    "In this sequence of tutorials, we will learn how to use TRIQS/ModEST to build electronic structure calculations of real strongly correrated materials using the union of an*ab initio* methods such as density-functional theory (DFT) or many-body perturbation theory (e.g., GW), with a many-body method like DMFT.\n",
    "\n",
    "Our tutorials will focus on La$_{2}$CuO$_{4}$, one of the parent compounds in the family of cuprate high-temperature superconductors. Although conventional DFT predicts a metallic solution, in reality it is a canonical example of a strongly correlated quantum material that exhibits rich physics, including  a Mott insulating state, antiferromagnetism, and upon doping, unconventional superconductivity. Despite its layered structure, the essential low-energy physics of La$_{2}$CuO$_{4}$ arises predominantly from the CuO$_{2}$ planes, where the Cu-$3d_{x^{2}-y^{2}}$ orbitals hybridize with the oxygen $2p$ states to form a narrow antibonding band near the Fermi level.\n",
    "\n",
    "To capture these phenomena, La$_{2}$CuO$_{4}$ is often modeled by an effective two-dimensional (2D) square lattice where each site hosts a single Cu-$3d_{x^2-y^2}$ orbital. The Hamilonian dictating the electronic behavior one this lattice is typically presumed to be a Hubbard-like Hamiltonian expressed as\n",
    "$$ H = \\sum_{ij\\sigma} t_{ij} c^\\dagger_{i\\sigma} c_{j\\sigma} - \\mu \\sum_{i\\sigma} n_{i\\sigma} + U \\sum_{i} n_{i\\uparrow} n_{i\\downarrow} $$\n",
    "where the first term is the kinetic part with $t_{ij}$ the hoping amplitude of an electron going from the orbital at site $i$ to the one at site $j$, the second term fixes the number of electrons in the effective model with $\\mu$ the chemical potential, and the last term is an electron-electron interaction, the one-site Coulomb repulsion determined by the Hubbard $U$ parameter.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following, we learn how one can extract a set of $t_{ij}$ parameters from a DFT calculation and then solve the corresponding Hubbard-like Hamiltonian using DMFT to understand better the physics of a real materials such as La$_2$CuO$_4$. In particular, here is the list of the tutorials that we propose, along with a short description of their main goal and the learning outcome:"
   ]
